{"id":"2110.05605","submitter":"Benjamin Jarman","authors":"Benjamin Jarman, Nathan Mankovich, Jacob D. Moorman","title":"Randomized Extended Kaczmarz is a Limit Point of Sketch-and-Project","comments":"18 pages, 14 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.NA cs.NA","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  The sketch-and-project (SAP) framework for solving systems of linear\nequations has unified the theory behind popular projective iterative methods\nsuch as randomized Kaczmarz, randomized coordinate descent, and variants\nthereof. The randomized extended Kaczmarz (REK) method is a popular extension\nof randomized Kaczmarz for solving inconsistent systems, which has not yet been\nshown to lie within the SAP framework. In this work we show that, in a certain\nsense, REK may be expressed as the limit point of a family of SAP methods, but\nwe argue that it is unlikely that REK can be translated into a SAP method\nitself. We provide an extensive theoretical analysis of the family of methods\ncomprising said limit, including convergence guarantees and further connections\nto REK. We follow this with an array of experiments demonstrating these methods\nand their connections in practice.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 11 Oct 2021 20:54:18 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 11 Apr 2022 22:00:49 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-04-13"}
